idCitation.collTitle: NOAA Fisheries, Northwest Fisheries Science Center, GIS Data Layers for 2012 Review of West Coast Groundfish Essential Fish Habitat

citRespParty.rpOrgName: Active Tectonics and Seafloor Mapping Lab, College of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Sciences, Oregon Sate Univeristy

dataIdInfo.idPurp: The main purpose of this data layer is to help inform a periodic review of groundfish essential fish habitat (EFH) off the U.S. West Coast by the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS) and the Pacific Fisheries Management Council (PFMC). The Magnuson-Stevens Fishery Conservation and Management Act (MSA)(16 USC 1801 et seq) defines EFH as “those waters and substrate necessary to fish for spawning, breeding, feeding, or growth to maturity,” and requires Fishery Management Councils (FMCs) to describe and identify EFH in fishery management plans (FMPs). The FMPs should identify EFH based on current distribution, habitat components, historical presence, or other factors; and should also identify habitat requirements at each life stage and research needs. FMPs must evaluate potential adverse impacts from both fishing and non-fishing activities, as well as minimize adverse effects of fishing to the extent practicable. FMPs should also identify habitat areas of particular concern (HAPC) within EFH based on the habitat’s ecological function, sensitivity to human-induced disturbance, rarity, or whether development activities may stress a particular habitat.
dataIdInfo.idCredit: Active Tectonics and Seafloor Mapping Lab at Oregon State Univeristy, College of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Sciences, Corvallis, Oregon, 97331

Consts.useLimit: This dataset is being made publically available for non-commercial use.

dataIdInfo.idAbs:
This data layer depicts the spatial distribution of seabed habitat types in the US West Coast Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ). The data layer was developed from 261 new map "sources" (sources to datasets may be one to many when more than one habitat map was made for or from a given source, or sources to datasets may be many to one where maps were compilation maps were made many sources). This layer incorporates 80 unique shapefile and 237 unique raster habitat datasets identified through the 2012 EFH Phase 1 Report (http://www.pcouncil.org/wp-content/uploads/H6b_EFHRC_RPT_1_SEP2012BB.pdf).

Input dataset credits (sources used for this mosaic were produced by the following researchers):

California State University Monterey Bay, Seafloor Mapping Lab; Moss Landing Marine Labs, Center for Habitat Studies; NOAA Olympic Coast national Marine Sanctuary; NOAA Fisheries, Fishery Resource Analysis and Monitoring Division; Oregon State University, Active Tectonics and Seafloor Mapping Lab; United States Geological Survey.

Input habitat map layers used to create this mosaic dataset in decending layer order (First Layer = Top, Last Layer = Bottom). Layers on top override layes below where they overlap in the mosaic.
